Reasoning: The claim that mice lacking Interferon-γ or its receptor exhibit high resistance to experimental autoimmune myocarditis is refuted by the evidence. Paper ID 24338780 states that "IFN-gamma receptor-deficient mice (IFN-gammaR(-/-)) on a BALB/c background immunized with a peptide derived from cardiac alpha-myosin heavy chain develop severe myocarditis." The abstract of this paper further concludes that "IFN-gamma protects mice from lethal autoimmune myocarditis." Similarly, paper ID 40632104 reports that "IFN-gamma-deficient mice developed fatal autoimmune disease," and its abstract indicates that "IFN-gamma production from these cells limits disease progression." Both sources consistently demonstrate that the absence of IFN-γ or its receptor leads to increased susceptibility and severity of autoimmune myocarditis, rather than resistance.
